42. Bleichenbacher's e=3 RSA Attack

Forging an RSA signature without the private key

Plain text:
hi mom

Goal:
Create a forged RSA signature that is accepted as valid

> Hashing the Plain Text

Using SHA-1

"hi mom" → SHA1 → HASH (20 bytes)

Example (hex form):
925a89b43f3caff507db0a86d20a2428007f10b6

> PKCS#1 v1.5 Block Structure

Standard format:
00 01 FF FF ... FF 00 ASN.1 HASH

Accepted structure (weak verification):
00 01 FF 00 ASN.1 HASH + remaining bytes

> ASN.1 Prefix (SHA-1)

ASN.1 = 3021300906052b0e03021a05000414

Constructed block:

00 01 FF 00
3021300906052b0e03021a05000414
HASH
00 00 00 00 00 ... (pad to 128 bytes)

Notes:
* Total size = 1024 bits (128 bytes)
* Remaining bytes filled with zeros

> Conversion

block → large integer value

> Cube Root Operation

Since e = 3

signature ≈ cube_root(block)

Adjustment:
signature = cube_root(block) + 1

> Forged Signature

signature → forged RSA signature

Verification:
signature^3 → reconstructed block

Resulting prefix:
00 01 FF 00 ASN.1 HASH ...

Notes:
* Only prefix is validated
* Full padding is not checked
* Remaining bytes ignored

Signature is accepted as valid

To make it easier and automatic...
CODE (Java)
        
        import java.math.BigInteger;
        import java.security.MessageDigest;
        
        public class BleichenbacherAttack {
        
        ```
        public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {  
        
            String message = "hi mom";  
        
            MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("SHA-1");  
            byte[] hash = md.digest(message.getBytes());  
        
            byte[] asn1 = new byte[]{  
                0x30,0x21,0x30,0x09,0x06,0x05,0x2b,0x0e,  
                0x03,0x02,0x1a,0x05,0x00,0x04,0x14  
            };  
        
            byte[] block = new byte[128];  
        
            block[0] = 0x00;  
            block[1] = 0x01;  
            block[2] = (byte)0xff;  
            block[3] = 0x00;  

            System.arraycopy(asn1, 0, block, 4, asn1.length);  
            System.arraycopy(hash, 0, block, 4 + asn1.length, hash.length);  
        
            BigInteger num = new BigInteger(1, block);  
        
            BigInteger sig = cubeRoot(num).add(BigInteger.ONE);  
        
            System.out.println(sig.toString(16));  
        }  
        
        public static BigInteger cubeRoot(BigInteger n) {  
            BigInteger low = BigInteger.ZERO;  
            BigInteger high = n;  

        while (low.compareTo(high) < 0) {  
            BigInteger mid = low.add(high).shiftRight(1);  
            BigInteger midCubed = mid.pow(3);  
    
            if (midCubed.compareTo(n) < 0)  
                low = mid.add(BigInteger.ONE);  
            else  
                high = mid;  
        }  
    
        return low;  
    }     
}

Notes:
> MessageDigest.getInstance("SHA-1")
  * computes hash of the message
> ASN.1 prefix
  * identifies SHA-1 structure
> byte[128]
  * 1024-bit RSA block size
> 00 01 FF 00
  * minimal padding used
> cubeRoot()
  * computes integer cube root
> +1 adjustment
  * ensures cube produces correct prefix

Summary:
-Construct a valid-looking block
-compute its cube root
-use result as forged signature

